NODE JS Features :
------------------------- >
# Non Blocking Input/outPut : 
>> Designed to perform non-blocking operations by default, making it Suitable for I/O-heavy operations

> In Node.js, everything revolves around events.
> Node.js does NOT wait for slow operations (I/O)

I/O = INput/outPut
file readings 
Database calls
Api requests 
network operations

# Networking Support:
>> Supports TCP/UDP sockets, which are crucial for building, lower, level, network applications that browsers can't handle.

#  File system Access: Provides API's to read and write files, directly which is not possible in browsers environments for security.

# Server-side Capabilities: Node. js enables javascript to run on the server, handling HTTP requests, file operations, and other server-side functionalities.

# Modules: Organize code in to reusable modules using requires().


Feature which are not there in the NODE:
------------------------------------------- >
> Window Object : The global window object , which is part of web browsers, is absent in node.js.

> DOM Manipulations: Node js does not have a built-in Document Object Model (DOM).

> BOM browser object model: No direct interactions with things like navigator or screen which are part of BOM in browsers.

> Web-Specific Apis: API's like localStorage, sessionStorage, and browser-based fetch are not available in node.js.




EVENT LOOP, WORKER THREAD, THREAD POOL:
============================================== >

Which mean when client is requested, 
that request will comes to the EVENT LOOP, then this 
event loop is single-thread, non blocking.
which means the event loop is having only single thread but it can handle multiple events at a time.
> when an request comes to the EVENT LOOP, then 
that request is taken by the EVENT LOOP and 
here, 
[[
    > Node.js uses a fixed thread pool (via libuv),
    > default size = 4 threads, 
    > Threads are reused, not created per request.
    ]]
If it is an light weight, then it will be handled by the EVENT-LOOP only, other wise 

it will assigns the task to an existing WORKER thread in the thread pool by calling to it.
If that Worker thread completed that work , then 
that work will be placed, in the callback queue, then
event loop picks that CALL-BACK and executes it,
sending the response to the clients.

Note : If the thread pool is full, Then tasks will be delayed, response time increases, But server does NOT crash.

Note: Yes, we can increase the Thread pool size,  Max : 128 

Note: Node.js is fast because it avoids threads- not because it uses many threads.

